ü¶† If you are not in an area where COVID-19 is spreading, or if you have not traveled from one of those areas or have not been in close contact with someone who has and is feeling unwell, your chances of getting it are currently low.

However, it‚Äôs understandable that you may feel stressed and anxious about the situation. It is important to be informed of the situation where you live and take appropriate measures to protect yourself.

ü¶† If you are in an area where there is an outbreak of COVID-19 you need to take the risk of infection seriously.
Follow the advice issued by national and local health authorities. Although for most people COVID-19 causes only mild illness, it can make some people very ill. More rarely, the disease can be fatal. Older people, and those with pre-existing medical conditions (such as high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes) appear to be more vulnerable.
ü¶† Okay, for which country?
ü¶† Good to know that you're ok  $name.</br>How may I help you today?

ü¶† Only wear a mask if you are ill with COVID-19 symptoms (especially coughing) or looking after someone who may have COVID-19. A disposable face mask can only be used once. </br></br>If you are not ill or looking after someone who is ill then you are wasting a mask. </br>There is a worldwide shortage of masks, so WHO urges people to use masks wisely.

ü¶† Take care of your health and protect others by doing the following:
1- Wash your hands 2- Keep social distance 3- Avoid touching eyes and mouth 4- Follow respiratory hygiene 5- Stay at home if feel unwell 6- Stay informed about COVID-19
ü¶†COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus. This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.

ü¶†Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses that may cause illness in animals or humans.
In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS).
The most recently discovered coronavirus causes coronavirus disease COVID-19.

ü¶† Okay, initially the recommendation for you is to stay at home if you begin to feel unwell, even with mild symptoms such as headache and a slight runny nose, until you recover.

Avoiding contact with others and visits to medical facilities will help to protect you and others from possible exposure to COVID-19.
If the symptoms still persist contact local health assistance for more instructions.

ü¶† The risk depends on where you live or where you have traveled recently. The risk of infection is higher in areas where a number of people have been diagnosed with COVID-19.
More than 95% of all COVID-19 cases are occurring in China, with the majority of those in Hubei Province. For people in most other parts of the world, your risk of getting COVID-19 is currently low, however, it‚Äôs important to be aware of the situation and preparedness efforts in your area.

values.text: ü¶† While we are still learning about how COVID-2019 affects people, older persons and persons with pre-existing medical conditions (such as high blood pressure, heart disease, or diabetes) appear to develop serious illness more often than others.

values: ü¶† Not yet. To date, there is no vaccine and no specific antiviral medicine to prevent or treat COVID-2019. However, those affected should receive care to relieve symptoms. People with serious illness should be hospitalized. Most patients recover thanks to supportive care.

values.text: ü¶† There is no specific treatment for disease caused by a novel coronavirus. However, many of the symptoms can be treated and therefore treatment based on the patient‚Äôs clinical condition. Moreover, supportive care for infected persons can be highly effective.

ü¶† The ‚Äúincubation period‚Äù means the time between catching the virus and beginning to have symptoms of the disease. Most estimates of the incubation period for COVID-19 range from 1-14 days, most commonly around five days. These estimates will be updated as more data become available.

ü¶† Ok, The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are dry cough, fever, breathing difficulties, and tiredness. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhoea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually.

Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms and don't feel unwell.
Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment.
